&lt;p&gt;Quoting &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.katycowan.co.uk/blog/getting-old&#34;&gt;Katy Cowan&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;this really resonated with me today. Emphasis my own.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We were the kids who missed the first wave of acid house but still got swept up in the afterglow. We straddle the line between Gen X and Millennials — the so-called Xennials. We grew up analogue and came of age in the digital revolution. We spent more time climbing trees, riding bikes and playing football than we looked at any screen. We remember our landline numbers (mine had four digits), taping songs off the radio, and the thrill of a HMV shopping spree. We experienced life without social media, but we also remember getting our first Nokia and the magic of MSN Messenger. And we watched in awe as computers went from enormous desktop towers to sleek little rectangles we now carry around in our pockets.&lt;/p&gt;
